      <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>

      <section id="conclusion">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Personal risk assessment transforms risk from a feeling into a framework. By evaluating probability, magnitude, reversibility, and time horizon — and checking each against your actual risk capacity — you build a clear picture of what you're actually signing up for. The goal isn't to eliminate risk, which is impossible, or to maximize risk tolerance, which is naive. It's to take risks that are genuinely asymmetric: bounded downside, significant upside, and within your capacity to absorb the worst case. That combination, applied consistently, produces dramatically better outcomes than either risk aversion or undifferentiated risk-taking.</p>

        <ContentBox type="tip" title="Your Next Step">
          Take one major decision you're currently facing and run it through all four dimensions. Write the answers down. You will almost certainly discover either that the risk is lower than it felt, or that a specific dimension is more dangerous than you'd realized. Both outcomes are valuable.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

